

<worksheet xml:id="A16_More-fitting-nonlinear-curves">
  <title>Math 150  Activity 16: More fitting nonlinear curves</title>
  <p>
    \sisetup{group-separator={{,}}, group-minimum-digits={3}}
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In this example we want to use a
        <em>power model</em>, left, to
        fit the data at right.
        <me>
          Q = Pw^y \qquad \qquad \qquad \begin{array}{|c||r|r|r|r|}
          \hline
          w \amp  \num{3000} \amp  \num{4500} \amp  \num{10000} \amp  \num{300000} \\ \hline
          Q \amp  10 \amp  15 \amp  25 \amp  175 \\ \hline
          \end{array}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Here the input variable,
        <m>w</m>, is raised to a fixed constant power <m>y</m>.
      </p>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          We will need to adjust the formula using logarithms.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="20%">
        <p>
          Write the system of equations and the vector equation using
          your previous answer and the data table.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          Use the <c>project</c> command to find the best-fit coefficients
          for your equation.
        </p>

        <p>
          { R gives <fillin characters="10"/> for the
          <c>(intercept)</c> and <fillin characters="10"/> for <c>log(w)</c>.}
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          What is the best-fit model? (Some adjustments will be required
          to the values you obtained from R.)
        </p>
      </task>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <pagebreak />

  <exercise workspace="20%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fit the same data points <m>(1,2)</m>,
        <m>(2,5)</m>, <m>(5,4)</m>, and
        <m>(7,3)</m> to the model <m>g(t) = a + b \sin{\left( \frac{2\pi}{16} t \right)}
        + c \cos{\left( \frac{2\pi}{16} t \right)}</m>.
      </p>

      <figure>

        <sidebyside>
          <task>
            <p>
              Write a system of equations that corresponds to the
              desired model.
            </p>
          </task>

          <p>
            \begin{task} Put your system of equations into vector form.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

      </figure>

      \end{task}

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          Write down the R commands to find the best values for <m>a</m>,
          <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
          Write the best-fitting function <m>g(t)</m> in the
          provided blank.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task>
        <p>
          Fill in the indicated values and compare your model to the
          original data.
        </p>

        <sidebyside>
          <p>
            Modeled values:
            <md>
              <mrow>g(1) \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
              <mrow>[3ex]
              g(2) \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
              <mrow>[3ex]
              g(5) \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
              <mrow>[3ex]
              g(7) \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Actual data:
            <md>
              <mrow>x = 1, y \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
              <mrow>[3ex]
              x = 2, y \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
              <mrow>[3ex]
              x = 5, y \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
              <mrow>[3ex]
              x = 7, y \amp = \lt fillin characters="10"/></mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

      </task>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>

